Of the three &quot; ranger type &quot; classes, here is the info i know from talking to beta testers, and doing a LOT of research.<br>
<br>
They are :<br>
<br>
Hunter - Midguard<br>
Ranger - Hibernia<br>
Scout  - Albion<br>
**Warden - Hibernia<br>
<br>
This is if you define &quot;uses bows&quot; as a primary feature of rangers.  All three of these classes use bows as main weapons.<br>
<br>
Currently, of these three classes, the &quot;hunter&quot; class from midguard is FAR above the other classes in overall usefulness, and power.<br>
<br>
&quot;rangers&quot; from hibernia are currently not a viable class.  They are dual wielders, but dual wielding doesnt seem to work properly yet ( all of the dual wielding classes seem to have issues atm ).  They have no spells, and will get creamed by any melee who closes with them.<br>
<br>
&quot;Scouts&quot; from albion are actually a decent class, but not really a &quot; ranger&quot;.  They have a rogue base, and are great bow users, with slightly below average melee.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wardens&quot; from Hibernia could be called paladins i guess.. but i would more liken them to a fighter / druid type.<br>
<br>
Keep in mind that in Hibernia, druids ARE the &quot; clerics &quot; of the realm.  The &quot;warden&quot; depending on how he spends his skill points, could be a primary healer in a group.  He gets several heal spells, and rezz.  He uses a bow as a pulling type tool, not as main damage, and has some nice self buffs.<br>
<br>
Hunters still have a CLEAR current advantage ( like a couple midguard  toons atm ).  Some say they should be nerfed.  Honestly, they dont need to nerf hunters, they need to buff the similar classes so they can bring as much to the table as a hunter can.  <br>
<br>
From ALL accounts, Hunters are &quot; fun &quot; to play ( which is the purpose, to have fun ), so the other classes like this should be &quot;fun&quot; too.<br>
<br>
Midguard thanes also suffer from this problem, and are probably ( with the hunter ) the 2 most powerful classes in the game currently.  <br>
<br>
I get this from doing research, and speaking to beta people.  Anyone in beta please feel free to correct me if i have misinformation.<br>
<br>
